  1. Plot a beta(3, 5) pdf and a beta(5, 11) pdf on the same graph; the beta(3,5) should be in black and the beta(5,11) in gray. Also, be sure to properly format this graphic (x- and y-axes, overall title, and a legend).
X <- seq(0,1,length.out=1001)
plot(X,dbeta(X,shape1 = 5, shape2 = 11), 
     col = 'black', lwd = 2, type = 'l',
     main = 'Beta(3,5) & Beta(5,11)',
     xlab = 'X',
     ylab = 'f(x)')
lines(X,dbeta(X, shape1 = 3, shape2 = 5),
      col = 'gray', lwd = 2)
legend(.75, 3, legend=c("Beta(5,11)", "Beta(3,5)"),
       col=c("black", "gray"), lty = 1, lwd = 2, cex = 1)

    Conditional * Prior

  4. Refer again to question 4. Create one figure with two plots (i.e., use par(mfrow=c(1,2))). Each plot will contain two curves, a red one representing the prior distribution of θ and a blue representing the posterior distribution of θ. For the left plot, use a beta(1,1) prior distribution. Comment on what this prior distribution implies regarding prior beliefs of the analyst and the impact it has on the posterior. For the right plot, use a beta(25,1) prior distribution. Comment on what this prior distribution implies regarding prior beliefs of the analyst and the impact it has on the posterior.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
x <- 3
n <- 11
X <- seq(0,1,length.out=1001)
prior1 <- dbeta(X,shape1=1,shape2=1)
post1 <- dbeta(X,shape1=1+x, shape2=1+n-x)
plot(X,post1, 
     col = 'blue', lwd = 2, type = 'l',
     main = 'Plot 1: Prior Belief Beta(1,1)',
     xlab = expression(theta),
     ylab = 'density')
lines(X,prior1,
      col = 'red', lwd = 2)
legend(.4, 3.15, legend=c("Prior", "Posterior"),
       col=c("red", "blue"), lty = 1, lwd = 2, cex = 1)

prior2 <- dbeta(X,shape1=25,shape2=1)
post2 <- dbeta(X,shape1=25+x, shape2=1+n-x)
plot(X,prior2, 
     col = 'blue', lwd = 2, type = 'l',
     main = 'Plot 2: Prior Belief Beta(25,1)',
     xlab = expression(theta),
     ylab = 'density')
lines(X,post2,
      col = 'red', lwd = 2)
legend(0, 25, legend=c("Prior", "Posterior"),
       col=c("red", "blue"), lty = 1, lwd = 2, cex = 1)

For plot 1, the analyst has no prior inclination as to what the parameters are, so they assign a uniform distribution as the prior belief. This does not really impact the posterior that much.

For plot 2, the analyst has a strong prior belief that \(theta\) is very close to 1. This heavily influences the posterior, so while the posterior mitigates that prior belief, the posterior distibution does not match our MLE.
